<main class="container">
  <section class="project-hero">
    <span class="kicker">Current project</span>
    <h1>Adaptive Interview Preparation Coach</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      An interview-prep platform built around one practical question: what should the user study right now, and why?
    </p>
    <p class="supporting">
      I wanted to build something more opinionated than a flashcard tool. The point is to reduce the mental load of deciding what to practise and to make progress visible.
    </p>
    <div class="meta-grid">
      <div>
        <strong>Current direction</strong>
        Django, PostgreSQL, modular monolith, iterative delivery
      </div>
      <div>
        <strong>Development style</strong>
        Small milestones, test-driven development, and progressive product shaping
      </div>
      <div>
        <strong>Future layer</strong>
        RAG support for grounded notes, examples, and explanations
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="split">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="section-head">
        <h2>The product idea</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        Most interview-prep tools help people store content. I am interested in a different problem. Interview prep already takes a lot of effort. Deciding what to study every day adds another layer of friction.
      </p>
      <p>
        This project is meant to help with planning, prioritisation, and feedback. It should tell the user what to study, why it matters, how to approach it, and when to revisit it.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="section-head">
        <h2>Why I like this problem</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        It brings together backend architecture, product design, learning behaviour, and future AI support. It also fits the way I naturally think. The hardest part is not only storing information. It is deciding what should happen next.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="section-head">
      <h2>What exists in the plan now</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="grid two">
      <article class="project-card">
        <h3>Structured question library</h3>
        <p>
          Technical, behavioural, and debugging content modelled as distinct question types rather than forcing everything into one generic shape.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="project-card">
        <h3>Practice and review history</h3>
        <p>
          A history of what the user studied, where they struggled, and what needs to come back again later.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="project-card">
        <h3>Deterministic planning</h3>
        <p>
          Recommendations based on the interview goal, time available, topic coverage, weak areas, and review history.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="project-card">
        <h3>Future grounded support</h3>
        <p>
          A later RAG layer for notes, examples, and explanations, built as a support system rather than the core brain of the product.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="section-head">
      <h2>Build principles</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="grid three">
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Structure first</h3>
        <p>
          Planning, coverage, and review logic should be explicit and testable.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Iterative delivery</h3>
        <p>
          I would rather have a small working slice than a large vague plan.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>TDD</h3>
        <p>
          Behaviour comes first, then implementation. That keeps the product honest as it grows.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="section-head">
      <h2>Why it matters in my portfolio</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <p>
